President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring May 18 through May 24, 2014, as World Trade Week. In the proclamation, he highlights the importance of trade in building partnerships between nations and spurring economic growth. He emphasizes the role of trade in supporting American small businesses, creating jobs, and promoting exports. The President mentions the National Export Initiative (NEI), which has helped American businesses and farmers sell their products abroad and supported millions of American jobs. He also discusses the launch of a new phase of the NEI, called NEI/NEXT, which aims to assist companies in finding export opportunities and accessing financing. The President notes the importance of investing in cutting-edge manufacturing techniques to strengthen American companies' global competitiveness. He highlights ongoing trade negotiations, such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership and the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership, which aim to lower trade barriers and open up markets for American exports. The President concludes by urging Americans to observe World Trade Week with events, trade shows, and educational programs that celebrate and inform about the benefits of trade.